I use Waterbabies Pure and Simple because it is highly recommended by Consumer Reports, however I have so many stains on my colored cotton clothing from using it.  What is the best way to get those stains out of my clothes.  Love the product, but I need your help!

Hi Debra. Here are some suggestions for stain removal:

Wash clothing with a heavy duty detergent.

If the water has a high iron content, use water softener (not to be confused with fabric softener).

Be sure to wash and rinse clothing in water with water softener.

Waterless hand cleaners are sometimes effective.

Heat and chlorine bleach make the problem worse if the problem is from iron content. If the stain is still present, launder with a commercial rust remover. Commercial rust removers are for use only on white or colorfast fabrics.

If iron content in water is not an issue: pre treat the stain with a heavy duty liquid detergent or make a paste with powder detergent and water and let this set on fabric at least 30 minutes or overnight for tough stains. Then launder as usual. Check clothing before drying. If stain remains, repeat. It may also be effective is to soak clothing in a strong solution of a non chlorine bleach for colored fabrics and then launder as usual.

We are sorry to hear about your experience with the staining. If you haven't done so, please call our Contact Center at 1-866-288-3330 M-F 9AM – 5PM to speak with our team. Thanks.

Don't disrespect the flag!

4 U.S. Code § 8 - Respect for flag

Current through Pub. L. 114-19. (See Public Laws for the current Congress.)

US CodeNotes

No disrespect should be shown to the flag of the United States of America; the flag should not be dipped to any person or thing. Regimental colors, State flags, and organization or institutional flags are to be dipped as a mark of honor.

(a) The flag should never be displayed with the union down, except as a signal of dire distress in instances of extreme danger to life or property.

(b) The flag should never touch anything beneath it, such as the ground, the floor, water, or merchandise.

(c) The flag should never be carried flat or horizontally, but always aloft and free.

(d) The flag should never be used as wearing apparel, bedding, or drapery. It should never be festooned, drawn back, nor up, in folds, but always allowed to fall free. Bunting of blue, white, and red, always arranged with the blue above, the white in the middle, and the red below, should be used for covering a speaker’s desk, draping the front of the platform, and for decoration in general.

(e) The flag should never be fastened, displayed, used, or stored in such a manner as to permit it to be easily torn, soiled, or damaged in any way.

(f) The flag should never be used as a covering for a ceiling.

(g) The flag should never have placed upon it, nor on any part of it, nor attached to it any mark, insignia, letter, word, figure, design, picture, or drawing of any nature.

(h) The flag should never be used as a receptacle for receiving, holding, carrying, or delivering anything.

(i) The flag should never be used for advertising purposes in any manner whatsoever. It should not be embroidered on such articles as cushions or handkerchiefs and the like, printed or otherwise impressed on paper napkins or boxes or anything that is designed for temporary use and discard. Advertising signs should not be fastened to a staff or halyard from which the flag is flown.

(j) No part of the flag should ever be used as a costume or athletic uniform. However, a flag patch may be affixed to the uniform of military personnel, firemen, policemen, and members of patriotic organizations. The flag represents a living country and is itself considered a living thing. Therefore, the lapel flag pin being a replica, should be worn on the left lapel near the heart.

(k) The flag, when it is in such condition that it is no longer a fitting emblem for display, should be destroyed in a dignified way, preferably by burning.

Always look for the expiration date on Coppertone products. It is often hard to see or find, but it is there. Sunscreen bought on sale, may be left over from the prior selling season, and put back on the shelves a year later. It really does expire and turns into cooking oil. Never use left over sunscreen more than one season old . Coppertone  does acknowledge their products expire, few companies do. There is no FDA requirement to put an expiration date on sunscreens.  Luckily Coppertone does puts this info. on their products. As a swimmer ,W.S.I. and former lifeguard, I have had to learn about sunscreen through trial and error. It's the error that comes back to haunt you years later.

Hi Stephanie, We are so sorry to hear about your children's clothes.  The Coppertone product that you used provides broad spectrum protection from the sun, which is important as families prepare to enjoy time outdoors.  Many broad spectrum sunscreens may stain some clothing in a variety of circumstances.  One example of what may cause this staining is when the sunscreen is mixed in water with a high mineral content, which can be common in some regions of the country.  Staining may also occur when the sunscreen is not dry before coming in contact with fabrics.  That is why Coppertone is labeled with a warning about the potential for damaging or staining some fabrics or surfaces.  Merck Consumer Care takes consumers’ experiences with our products seriously.  Thank you for your note and we hope you have a nice week.
